	<text>
		<body>
			<div>

	<pb n="0001" facs="liv_002428_0001"/><!--pb/@n='1'-->
<!--Hand 01 58 top left--><!--hand 02 57469 top right-->
<lb/><p rend="right"><unclear cert="low">Cambala Hill</unclear></p>
<lb/><p rend="right">30 <choice><abbr>Oct<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi></abbr><expan>October</expan></choice> 1865</p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">My Dear Sir</p>
<lb/><p>On <choice><sic>recieving</sic><corr>receiving</corr></choice>
<lb/>your note I wrote 
<lb/>to <choice><abbr>Col</abbr><expan>Colonel</expan></choice> Taylor &amp; 
<lb/>he spoke to the 
<lb/>Sultan about the 
<lb/>Captains disobliging 
<lb/>conduct. The 
<lb/>Sultan thought 
<lb/>matters would 
<lb/>all come smooth 

	<pb n="0002" facs="liv_002428_0002"/><!--pb/@n='2'-->
<lb/>This was not at all 
<lb/>satisfactory and 
<lb/>set me to find out 
<lb/>some other means 
<lb/>of influencing 
<lb/>Captain Mahomet. 
<lb/>but I found out 
<lb/>that he is a great 
<lb/>drunkard whom 
<lb/>the Sultan cannot 
<lb/>get on well without 
<lb/>So I have to 
<lb/>submit somewhat 

	<pb n="0003" facs="liv_002428_0003"/><!--pb/@n='3'-->
<lb/>in the same way 
<lb/>that the Sultan 
<lb/>has to do, and I 
<lb/>hope that the 
<lb/>beasts &amp; men 
<lb/>may arrive 
<lb/>safely in spite 
<lb/>of him. I formerly 
<lb/>met a Captain 
<lb/>who had this 
<lb/>man on board 
<lb/>from England &amp; 
<lb/>the only way of 
<lb/>keeping him 
<lb/>sober was to deny 

	<pb n="0004" facs="liv_002428_0004"/><!--pb/@n='4'-->
<lb/>having any more 
<lb/>spirits aboard!</p>
<lb/><p>Thanking you 
<lb/>for the trouble 
<lb/>you kindly took</p>
<lb/><p>I am sincerely yours</p>
<lb/><p>David Livingstone</p>
<lb/>
<lb/>
<lb/>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">Captain Lucas</p>

	<pb n="0005" facs="liv_002428_0005"/><!--pb/@n='5'-->
<!--<note type="editorial" anchored="true">notes in different hand</note>--><!--hand 02 57469 top right-->
<lb/><p rend="center">David Livingstone</p>
<lb/><p>Born 1817 - died</p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">African traveller and missionary</p>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent">In 1856. D<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Livingstone had during 
<lb/>his <unclear cert="low">16</unclear> years <unclear cert="high">wandering</unclear> travelled no 
<lb/>less than 11,000 miles, whilst 
<lb/>endeavouring <unclear cert="high">to</unclear> spread the blessing 
<lb/>of Christianity <unclear cert="high">thru</unclear> lands never before 
<lb/>trodden by the foot of an European. 
<lb/>He subsequently laid down his life 
<lb/>in his noble endeavour <unclear cert="high">to</unclear>  check the 
<lb/><space extent="1" unit="words"/>slave trade.</p>
			
